        <h1 class='process-name'>Words to Song</h1>        
        <p>
            Every designer should have a portfolio–that’s a given. 
            It might also seem like a given in how to decide the design of said portfolio: 
            subscribe to WordPress or SquareSpace and pick one of their fancy templates. 
            Super simple, easy-peasy. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Perhaps that would be the method for some designers. 
            For me, however, every aspect of the layout and design has been meticulously thought out in terms of look and functionality. 
            Not only is this the case because I wanted a professional looking representation of my work and abilities, but also due to my decision to code the website from scratch. 
            And as a user experience designer, I wanted complete control over how my website would be interacted with.
        </p>
        <p>
            With that said, I knew there wasn’t a need to revolutionize the online portfolio. 
            Practicality, intuitivity, and cleanliness were the important factors in the design.

        <h3 class='process-head'>Initial Research</h3>
        <p>
            Naturally, one of the main sources of inspiration was the vast number of other online portfolios I explored. 
            While many did, indeed, use CMS templates as a framework, there is certainly value to be taken from those designs. 
            It shouldn’t be discounted that templates are used and work for a reason. 
            However, I wanted to make sure my personality came through in the look and feel, so as to not fall victim into the ubiquitousness that can sometimes happen with template designs.
        </p>
        <p>
            A second source of inspiration came from designs of Software as a Service (SaaS) websites. 
            While also following a broad formula in layout, many SaaS sites do an amazing job at succinctly giving information of the product, providing examples, and providing a call-to-action.
        </p>
