        <p>
            One particular feature I wanted to adopt from a number of SaaS designs, was the single-page interface (meaning the site virtually exists on one page). 
            The fewer pages users would need to navigate, the better chances I would have to keep them engaged with my content.
            Another benefit of the single-page layout is that it is much easier to navigate on mobile.
            With that in mind, I made sure to design the site responsive to mobile displays, as well.
        </p>
        <p>
            Like many SaaS websites, I wanted to give a sense of who I am as a person and designer at the top. 
            While some portfolios immediately dive into the examples of work, it’s part of my philosophy to let visitors (and by extension, future colleagues) know who the person is behind the work. 
            Then, I tell my professional story naturally on the way down by going into my background and skills, then finally examples of work. 
            Of course not everyone buys into that philosophy, so having quick anchor links to desired content (resume, portfolio, contact) was also a feature I wanted to implement.
        </p>    
         <p>
            In the resume section, I felt that rehashing the content on my official resume was not the most effective or interesting way to represent the information for visitors. 
            Therefore a quick look at my experience highlights and an overview of my hard skills would be the best hook. 
            If they are compelled to review my official resume, I decided that also offering links to both the PDF version and my LinkedIn profile would give a comprehensive look at my experiences and skills.
        </p> 
         <p>
            The portfolio section made most sense to be broken up into three parts: UX/UI/Web Development, Graphic Design, and Illustrations to give representation of my eclectic design background. 
            With a desire to keep things clean and simple, I coded simple drop down menus with JavaScript. 
        </p> 
        
        <h3 class='process-head'>Color Update</h3>
        <p>
            While often overlooked, color can have an important role in the experience of a portfolio. 
            In my initial design, the black/gray/cyan combo was sleek, but gave off a colder vibe than what I wanted, and it especially didn’t fit into my personality.
        </p> 
        <p>
            I knew a deep blue would be incorporated, not only as it is my favorite color, but it conveys trust, friendliness, and professionalism in color theory. 
            Combined with a lighter blue and more neutral  cream color to provide better readability and balance, the palette brings out a more personal flavor and warmth (while still on the cool spectrum).
        </p>
